The machine learning infrastructure of tensorlfow is highly flexible.
When I was implementing models from <<Tensorflow Cookbook>>, I could choose from all kinds of loss functions and Input/Output formats.
Regression and classification  can be done with similar archetechture as long as I set the corresponding loss functions and optimiztation methods.

While practicing, I experienced the thing described in the ML tutorials,
The batch size and its ramdomness are so important that  they can make final result totally different.
Plotting with python showed the Gamma values' importance in controlling overfitting of a SVM model.

The Machine learning is indeed an area that requires a lot of practice.

Now I've implemented several CNNs on recognition of hand written digits.
And I gained some basic knowledge of the four types of neural network layers:Fully connected/Convolutional/Activation/Pooling.
I also downloaded tensorflow version of openpose source code and printed the most crucial parts.
I'll try to understand its structure.

